How lwc:if is Better than if:true?


Answer

1. Performance - Short-Circuit Evaluation

if:true - All conditions are checked and rendered.

<div if:true={isLoading}>Loading...</div>
<div if:true={hasError}>Error!</div>
lwc:if: Stops at the first true condition.

<div lwc:if={isLoading}>Loading...</div>
<div lwc:elseif={hasError}>Error!</div>
<div lwc:else>No data</div>
2. Better Readability

if:true - Hard to follow logic:

<div if:true={isAdmin}>Admin</div>
<div if:true={isManager}>Manager</div>
<div if:true={isUser}>User</div>
lwc:if - Clear decision flow:

<div lwc:if={isAdmin}>Admin</div>
<div lwc:elseif={isManager}>Manager</div>
<div lwc:else>User</div>
3. Safer UI States

if:true: Multiple flags can be true → Conflicting UI.

lwc:if: Only one block renders at a time.



When to Use which?

* Use if:true for independent toggles:

<!-- ✅ Independent permissions -->
<button if:true={canEdit}>Edit</button>
<button if:true={canDelete}>Delete</button>
* Use lwc:if for mutually exclusive states:

<!-- ✅ Only one state possible -->
<div lwc:if={isLoading}>Loading...</div>
<div lwc:elseif={hasError}>Error!</div>
<div lwc:else>Content</div>


Summary

lwc:if is better than if:true because:

Performance: Short-circuit evaluation stops at the first true condition

Readability: Creates clear logical chains instead of scattered conditions

Safety: Guarantees mutually exclusive states

Efficiency: Creates fewer DOM nodes and evaluations

Maintainability: Easier to debug and modify complex conditional logic

However, if:true still has its place for independent boolean checks like permissions or feature flags.
